%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Introduction}
\label{chap:intro}
%******************************************************************************

%claude:
The goal of this book is to explain with full details the source code of
a {web browser}.

\section{Motivations}

%claude:
Why a web browser?
Because I think you are a better programmer if you fully understand how
things work under the hood, and the web browser is the program through
which most computer users now reach the rest of the software stack.
%
A web browser sits above the \unix-like user-space API
(see the \book{Libcore}),
above a windowing system (see the \book{Windows} and the \book{Widgets}),
above the network stack (see the \book{Network}),
and above the kernel (see the \book{Kernel}).
%
It exercises almost every layer of a modern operating system in one
program: a parser, an interpreter of a text protocol, a concurrent
I/O engine, a rendering engine, and an event-driven GUI.

%claude:
Most users spend hours every day inside a web browser: reading,
writing, watching, shopping, working.
%
%modern:
Modern engines---Gecko (Firefox), WebKit (Safari), Blink (Chrome)---have
become some of the most complex pieces of software ever written,
each counting in the millions of lines of code.
They implement full CSS box layouts, JavaScript virtual machines
with just-in-time compilers, GPU-accelerated compositing, sandboxing,
and dozens of other features accreted over three decades.
It is no longer realistic for a single programmer to understand
all of that in one lifetime.

%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
Yet the {essence} of a browser is still very simple: fetch a document
over a network protocol, parse a markup language, render the result,
follow hyperlinks on demand. That essence, stripped of the modern
accretions, is what [[mothra]]---the \plan web browser I will describe
in this book---actually implements, in about 4400 lines of C.

%claude:
There are surprisingly few books explaining how a web browser works.
%cs-history:
The best I know of is \emph{Web Browser Engineering}~\cite{browser-engineering},
an online textbook that builds a toy browser in Python.
%
\principia complements that by showing the full source code of a
{real} browser---one that you can still launch today on \plan and
use to read real web pages, including over HTTPS.

%claude:
Here are a few questions I hope this book will answer:

\begin{itemize}

\item What happens when the user types a URL in the address bar?
What is the trace of such a request through the different layers
of the software stack?

\item What does HTTP look like in practice, at the byte level?
How does HTTPS add confidentiality on top?

\item How is HTML turned into something you can see and click on?
Does mothra build a DOM tree? If not, what does it build instead?

\item Why does \plan expose HTTP as a filesystem ([[/mnt/web]])
rather than as a library to link?
What does that design buy over a conventional [[libcurl]]?

\item How are cookies stored and scoped? Why is [[webcookies]] a
separate file server from [[webfs]]?

\item How does a browser handle character encodings (UTF-8, Latin-1,
Shift-JIS, GB2312, \ldots) without getting tangled in charset logic?

\item How are images fetched, decoded, and scaled?
Why do mothra's images go through three cooperating subprocesses?

\item What does mothra {not} do, and why?
No CSS, no JavaScript, no DOM---is such a browser still useful in 2026?

\end{itemize}

\section{The \plan web browser: [[mothra]]}

%claude:
I will explain in this book the code of the \plan web browser
[[mothra]]~\cite{mothra}\footnote{See
\url{http://man.9front.org/1/mothra} for its manual page.},
which contains about 4400 lines of C code (LOC), together
with the supporting file servers and pipeline tools it relies on:
[[webfs]] (4500 LOC), [[webcookies]] (1300 LOC), [[hget]] (1500 LOC),
[[tcs]] (charset conversion), [[uhtml]] (HTML charset preprocessor),
[[resize]] (image scaling), and [[getpix]] (image subprocess fetcher).

%claude:
%dup: Shell.nw
Like for most books in \principia, I chose a \plan program because
those programs are simple, small, elegant, open source, and
they form together a coherent set.
%
Moreover, [[mothra]] is arguably simpler to use and to understand
than any of the modern browser engines, or even than text-mode
browsers like [[lynx]]~\cite{lynx} or [[links]]~\cite{links}
(the most popular text browsers on \unix).

%claude:
%cs-history:
[[mothra]] descends from [[webpage]], one of the very first graphical
web browsers, written by Tom Duff at Bell Labs shortly after
Tim Berners-Lee released the first description of the web in 1991.

%claude:
%plan9-is-cleaner:
Despite its age, [[mothra]] still works: you can point it at a real HTTPS
URL today and it will fetch the page, parse the HTML, and render the text.
That is a remarkable property for a 30-year-old program, and one this
book will try to explain. The short version is that [[mothra]] delegates
nearly everything that changes (TLS cipher suites, HTTP header trends,
cookie standards) to helper programs and file servers beneath it, so the
browser code itself does not need to move.

\section{Other web browsers}

%claude:
Web browsers fall into three broad families: text-mode browsers,
classic graphical browsers, and modern engines.

%claude:
%cs-history:
The text-mode family---[[lynx]] (1992), [[links]] (2000),
[[w3m]] (1995)---renders HTML as reflowed text on a terminal.
They are small (20--80 kLOC), fast, usable over SSH, and good at
reading documents. They share with [[mothra]] the fundamental
simplification of treating HTML as a flow of text with inline
markup rather than a box-model layout. Where [[mothra]] differs
is that it runs inside a graphical windowing system
(see the \book{Windows}) and can display inline images;
the text browsers cannot.

%claude:
%cs-history:
The classic graphical family started with NCSA Mosaic (1993),
the first browser to popularize inline images. Netscape Navigator
(1994) commercialized Mosaic's design, Microsoft Internet Explorer
(1995) cloned Netscape, and the two fought the ``browser wars'' of
the late 1990s. All of these browsers were roughly in [[mothra]]'s
weight class (tens of thousands of LOC) and all implemented
HTML~2 or HTML~3.2 without JavaScript or CSS---exactly the subset
[[mothra]] still handles.

%claude:
%modern:
The modern family consists of three rendering engines:
{Gecko} (powering Firefox, from Netscape's 1998 open-source release),
{WebKit} (powering Safari, forked from KHTML in~2001), and
{Blink} (powering Chrome, Edge, Opera, forked from WebKit in~2013).
Each engine counts in the millions of LOC and implements the full
modern web platform: CSS Grid and Flexbox layouts, a JavaScript engine
(V8, SpiderMonkey, JavaScriptCore) with JIT compilation, WebGL,
WebAssembly, sandboxing, and much more.
A good engineer can understand a part of one of these engines in
a year of work; nobody understands all of them.

%claude:
%cs-history:
\plan itself has had more than one browser. [[mothra]]'s predecessor
was [[webpage]] by Tom Duff; its contemporary is [[abaco]] by Federico
Benavento, written in~2004 on top of [[libdraw]] directly (rather than
[[libpanel]], which [[mothra]] uses). [[abaco]] has slightly better
HTML~4 coverage through its use of [[libhtml]], a more thorough parser
library written by Russ Cox. I will compare the two in the Conclusion.

\begin{figure}[]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{lineage}
\caption{Web browsers timeline}
\label{fig:lineage}
\end{figure}

%dup: Shell.nw
%claude:
Figure~\ref{fig:lineage} presents a timeline of major web browsers.
%
I think [[mothra]] represents the best compromise for this book:
it implements the essential features of a graphical web browser while
still having a small and understandable codebase (about 4400 LOC),
and it composes cleanly with the other \plan tools covered elsewhere
in \principia.

\section{Getting started}

%claude:
To play with [[mothra]], you will first need to install the \plan fork
used in \principia (see \urlinstall).
%
Once booted, launch [[rio]] (the \plan windowing system, see
the \book{Windows}), start a new shell window, and type:
%
\begin{verbatim}
    % mothra http://example.com
\end{verbatim}
%
A new window will open showing the rendered page. Click on any link
to follow it; the address bar updates and mothra fetches the new page.
The arrow buttons navigate history; the text box lets you type a fresh URL.

%claude:
You can also pipe HTML directly into [[mothra]] for testing:
%
\begin{verbatim}
    % echo '<h1>Hello</h1><p>World' | mothra
\end{verbatim}
%
This is useful for driving the parser without a network.

\section{Requirements}

%claude:
This book assumes a good knowledge of the {C programming
language}~\cite{kr}. If that is not the case I suggest you first read
\emph{The C Programming Language}~\cite{kr} and possibly also
\emph{Advanced Programming in the Unix Environment}~\cite{apue}.

%claude:
Basic familiarity with HTTP and HTML is helpful but not required.
The \book{Network} provides the necessary background on TCP/IP
and \plan's [[/net]] filesystem.
%
The \book{Kernel} explains how the kernel exposes network devices
(including [[/net/tls]] for TLS) and how namespaces work, which is the
substrate on top of which [[webfs]] operates.
%
The \book{Libcore} covers the user-space C library: [[fork]],
[[exec]], [[pipe]], [[print]], and the~9P client library that
[[webfs]] uses to serve [[/mnt/web]].
%
The \book{Widgets} describes [[libpanel]], the widget toolkit mothra
uses to lay out its address bar, display area, status bar, and form
widgets.

%claude:
This is {not} an introduction to the web or to HTML. Readers wanting
a gentler walk through how a browser works from first principles can
read \emph{Web Browser Engineering}~\cite{browser-engineering} in
parallel with this book.

